T1  - The Price of Law: The Case of the Eurozone Collective Action Clauses
PY  - 2021
Y1  - 2021/12/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhaa140
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 34
IS  - 12
SP  - 5933
EP  - 5976
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We analyze the price effect of the introduction of collective action clauses (CACs) in newly issued sovereign bonds of eurozone countries as of January 1, 2013. By allowing a majority of creditors to modify payment obligations, such clauses reduce the likelihood of holdouts, while facilitating strategic default by the sovereign. We find that CAC bonds trade in the secondary market at lower yields than otherwise similar no-CAC bonds. The yield differential widens in countries with worse ratings and in those with stronger legal systems, especially if of midrange quality. Hence, CACs are seen as pro- rather than anticreditor provisions.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhaa140
ER  - 



