TY  - JOUR
AU  - Karpoff, Jonathan M
AU  - Schonlau, Robert
AU  - Suzuki, Katsushi
T1  - Shareholder Perks and Firm Value
PY  - 2021
Y1  - 2021/12/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhaa141
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 34
IS  - 12
SP  - 5676
EP  - 5722
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Shareholder perks are in-kind gifts or purchase discounts that disproportionately reward small shareholders. Data from Japanese firms indicate that firms initiating perk programs attract individual retail shareholders and experience increases in share values. We find support for three channels by which perks increase firm value: an increase in share liquidity, a decrease in the equity cost of capital, and signaling to investors. A fourth channel, by which perks help to market the firm’s products to consumers, receives mixed support. We do not find evidence that perk programs work to entrench managers.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhaa141
ER  - 



